  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"KMT2A oncoproteins induce epigenetic resistance to targeted therapies\" presents significant findings that have garnered attention in the academic community, with six citations across various prestigious journals. Backed by renowned institutions such as the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and Fred Hutch Cancer Center, this research contributes to an evolving understanding of targeted therapies in cancer treatment.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The recent preprint \"KMT2A oncoproteins induce epigenetic resistance to targeted therapies\" sheds light on the mechanisms of resistance exhibited by cancer cells, providing valuable insights for the ongoing battle against malignancies. Published in 2023 on bioRxiv, this work has already attracted six citations in reputable journals such as Cancers and Biomedicines, indicating its potential impact within the scientific community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research's institutional affiliations highlight the robust foundation from which it has emerged. Key institutions, including the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and Texas Children's Hospital, lend considerable credibility to the findings. Such affiliations not only reinforce the study's legitimacy but also signal a collaborative effort among top-tier research entities that enhances its overall quality and reach.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Though there are no public discussions or high-fidelity social media mentions recorded, the academic reception suggests a proactive engagement with the findings. The ability of this work to incite discourse among academics can be inferred from its citations in diverse countries, including the United States, United Arab Emirates, and Australia, showcasing its relevance across different geopolitical contexts.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the absence of funding acts as a testament to the commitment of the researchers to explore critical questions within the field without external financial influence. The study also exhibits a significant downstream reuse factor, with seven instances indicating that its findings have been foundational for subsequent research efforts, furthering our collective understanding of epigenetic resistance in cancer biology.</p>",
